Sealed types — a closed family of subtypes.

Normally a class or an interface in Java is open to extension by anyone, anywhere, at any time. Anyone in any package or any project can declare a new subclass. Sealed types let you say, these are the only types allowed to extend me. The compiler enforces the restriction. You write public sealed interface Shape permits Circle comma Square comma Triangle. Now no class anywhere in the world is allowed to implement Shape except those three. Java records pair beautifully with sealed types, because each subtype is just a one line record.
